I74Findings

I21Pub. L. 107ÿ09295, title I, ÿ1A101, Nov. 25, 2002, 116 Stat. 2066, provided that:

I21``The Congress makes the following findings:

I22``(1) There are 361 public ports in the United States that are an integral part of our Nation's commerce.

I22``(2) United States ports handle over 95 percent of United States overseas trade. The total volume of goods imported and exported through ports is expected to more than double over the next 20 years.

I22``(3) The variety of trade and commerce carried out at ports includes bulk cargo, containerized cargo, passenger transport and tourism, and intermodal transportation systems that are complex to secure.

I22``(4) The United States is increasingly dependent on imported energy for a substantial share of its energy supply, and a disruption of that share of supply would seriously harm consumers and our economy.

I22``(5) The top 50 ports in the United States account for about 90 percent of all the cargo tonnage. Twenty-five United States ports account for 98 percent of all container shipments. Cruise ships visiting foreign destinations embark from at least 16 ports. Ferries in the United States transport 113,000,000 passengers and 32,000,000 vehicles per year.

I22``(6) Ports often are a major locus of Federal crime, including drug trafficking, cargo theft, and smuggling of contraband and aliens.

I22``(7) Ports are often very open and exposed and are susceptible to large scale acts of terrorism that could cause a large loss of life or economic disruption.

I22``(8) Current inspection levels of containerized cargo are insufficient to counter potential security risks. Technology is currently not adequately deployed to allow for the nonintrusive inspection of containerized cargo.

I22``(9) The cruise ship industry poses a special risk from a security perspective.

I22``(10) Securing entry points and other areas of port facilities and examining or inspecting containers would increase security at United States ports.

I22``(11) Biometric identification procedures for individuals having access to secure areas in port facilities are important tools to deter and prevent port cargo crimes, smuggling, and terrorist actions.

I22``(12) United States ports are international boundaries that_

I23``(A) are particularly vulnerable to breaches in security;

I23``(B) may present weaknesses in the ability of the United States to realize its national security objectives; and

I23``(C) may serve as a vector or target for terrorist attacks aimed at the United States.

I22``(13) It is in the best interests of the United States_

I23``(A) to have a free flow of interstate and foreign commerce and to ensure the efficient movement of cargo;

I23``(B) to increase United States port security by establishing improving communication among law enforcement officials responsible for port security;

I23``(C) to formulate requirements for physical port security, recognizing the different character and nature of United States port facilities, and to require the establishment of security programs at port facilities;

I23``(D) to provide financial assistance to help the States and the private sector to increase physical security of United States ports;

I23``(E) to invest in long-term technology to facilitate the private sector development of technology that will assist in the nonintrusive timely detection of crime or potential crime at United States ports;

I23``(F) to increase intelligence collection on cargo and intermodal movements to address areas of potential threat to safety and security; and

I23``(G) to promote private sector procedures that provide for in-transit visibility and support law enforcement efforts directed at managing the security risks of cargo shipments.

